column3: habla sobre su experiencia en el miss earth 2018. tambien acusa a la organizacion de no hacer mucho por remover al sponsor de los eventos a pesar de las quejas presentadas de acoso sexual por una corona o clasificacion. dentro de la publicacion las concursantes miss earth wales 2017 & miss earth england 2017 relatan que pasaron por la misma experiencia en el miss earth 2017.  ninguna chica debería pasar por esas cosas a cambio de una corona o top!

column1: @miss.earth.england: es hora de hablar sobre mi experiencia personal. he estado en contacto cercano con mi director nacional y se han observado todos los incidentes. he trabajado muy duro para obtener mi título de miss earth england y
column3: tardé 4 años en llegar a la cima y ganar mi lugar en los internacionales. estaba encantada de representar finalmente a inglaterra en las hermosas filipinas. mi viaje fue una montaña rusa de emociones
column5: y no dejé el concurso ya que no iba a perder la experiencia. tengo muchos recuerdos hermosos de mi tiempo aquí en filipinas y muchos días maravillosos. conocí a felices filipinos que me mostraron tanta amabilidad y respeto. disfruté del 50% de mi viaje
column6: pero el otro 50% estuvo más que ensombrecido al sentirme explotada

column1: 250028;instagram;2018-11-07 16:03:19;FALSE;"elecciones dejan récord de mujeres en el congreso de eeuu
las elecciones de medio mandato en estados unidos han dejado un nuevo récord de mujeres elegidas para las dos cámaras del congreso
column3: frente a las 107 que hasta ahora ocupaban escaños.

column4: que se suman a las 10 senadoras que mantienen su escaño al no estar en juego

column2: muy críticas con el presidente donald trump
column3: han impulsado principalmente el avance electoral de los demócratas
column4: que han conseguido recuperar el control de la cámara de los representantes.

column3: y que se ha convertido en la congresista más joven de la historia de estados unidos
column4: es un claro símbolo de ese avance
column5: aunque no ha sido la única mujer e hispana en acceder al capitolio.

column1: verónica escobar y sylvia garcía comparten el honor de ser las primeras hispanas en representar a texas en el congreso
column4: dio una de las grandes sorpresas al imponerse a su rival en florida con más del 50 por ciento de los votos.

column1: otras mujeres destacadas que han llegado por primera vez a la cámara baja tienen ascendencia africana
column2: son indígenas o pertenecen a la comunidad lgtb (lesbianas
column8: serán las primeras musulmanas en el congreso.

column2: en enero dos indígenas se sentarán por primera vez en la cámara de representantes: deb haaland (nuevo méxico) y sharice davids
column3: que será además la primera persona abiertamente lgtb de kansas en el congreso.

column1: en las primeras elecciones de eeuu tras el nacimiento del movimiento #metoo (yo también)
column2: son varias las mujeres que han roto el techo de cristal y se han alzado por primera vez con cargos electos
column4: primera mujer senadora en la historia de tennessee.

column2: we made it. there was some heartbreak yesterday
column3: no doubt. but we flipped the house. impeachment is now on the table. we elected 100+ women to positions of power
column4: including many women of color. texas republicans were challenged for the first time in decades. i am so proud of everyone who went out and voted blue yesterday. and remember
column6: not a sprint. there is still so much work to be done. i was disappointed
column7: but unfortunately not surprised to see so many white women voting for republican candidates
column8: effectively choosing their white privilege over their womanhood. remember
column10: it isn’t feminism. i don’t mean to dampen anyone’s spirits—yesterday was a win! a big one! but like i said
column11: there is still so much work to be done. let’s keep going—together. keep voting. in every election. keep fighting voter suppression. keep fighting.

column1: wont let me wear bangles too;
would hide me a little more
and ask me not to go.
when i asked what school was
where had he been since last summer
saw her giving that bizarre nod
what she was sniffing the night before
learnt she was bitten by cold;
i'm out of words and through a gale
all the doors and windows closed;
a demon caught by your eyes
i know i would never be fine.
i remain behind that locked door
i want to have it all;
and look away when it's me;
and warned me not to go.

column1: 250137;instagram;2018-11-07 14:27:07;TRUE;;"soooo! yesterday was interesting! i have #downsizing #organizing business for seniors as you all know. there is always that one person you k ow is a negative nelly and no matter what the sun is never up and nothing good ever happens to them!! not to mention they are a energy vampire!
i had the pleasure of taking a client to the dr
column2: when he walked in the nurses said “hello welcome
column3: how are you doing today?” my client responds with “well i’m alive!” well hell to the yah
column4: i felt like screaming lol! you’re alive
column6: and the sun is shining down on our faces. why do you lock yourself up in a pit of darkness and save the world treats you like you’re nothing. if you treat yourself like you’re nothing
column7: then you  will become just that
column8: nothing-invisible-grumpy-bitter-not to mention angry! life is what you make it- in the meantime i’ll be pulling my head under the covers 😆🤣😂🤣 again today lol another trip to negative land!! so i put on my armor of protection- say my prayers for my shield & day my mantras for “i  am stronger than his negative vibes & i can & will be stronger for it!” @@@@@@@

column1: 250168;instagram;2018-11-07 13:53:08;FALSE;"rekordmånga kvinnor tar plats i usa:s kongress 🎩

2018 har kallats ”kvinnans år” bl a i kölvattnet av #metoo. runt om i världen ställer rekordmånga kvinnor upp i val till maktens rum. kvinnor som ofta har ett “ovanligt” cv. kvinnor med viktig kunskap och erfarenheter från samhället. vi ser unga kvinnor
column2: kvinnor ur minoriteter och hbtq-personer. i f! ställde rekordmånga upp i valet
column3: med över 60 namnlistor runt om i landet
column4: f! skrev historia. det betyder att vi som kämpar för mänskliga rättigheter faktiskt kliver fram och är motståndet mot fascismen.

column1: första gången i usa:s historia har fler än 100 kvinnor valts till kongressen.
💫 ilhan omar - första muslimska kvinnan att väljas till kongressen
💫 veronica escobar - första latinamerikanska kongresskvinnan från texas
💫 ayanna pressley - första svarta kvinnan att väljas till kongressen från massachusetts
💫 rashida tlaib - också första muslimska kvinnan att väljas till kongressen
💫 sharice davids - första kvinnan från usa:s ursprungsbefolkning att väljas till kongressen
💫 sylvia garcia - första latinamerikanska kongresskvinnan från texas
💫 alexandria ocasio-cortez - yngsta kvinnan någonsin att väljas till kongressen (29 år)

+ 💫 deb haaland - första kvinnan från usa:s ursprungsbefolkning och 💫 abby finkenauer - yngsta kvinnan någonsin (29 år) som inte fick plats på bild ❤️ vill du se fler som kämpar för mänskliga rättigheter i maktens rum?

column1: this data says more than the caption ccommunicates and it's an important discussion

black women and men are always seperated by the media and politics. and even more troubling to me is sistas are known as the foundation of the dem party as if 85% means nothing. in alabama 90% of black men voted to turn that state blue but you only heard about how black women decided that state's future bc of their voting at 94%. it's disgusting and troubling how easy it is to divide us when together black women and men would be a g-20 nation and flirting with g-8 power.

we have no allies. in 2010 white liberals stayed home and obama lost the house and senate to a group who should've been irrelevant for a generation after what happened during the bush era. no one shamed them for not voting but blacks are shamed? yet get nothing. why are the marginalized groups known as latinos and white women voting for gop? but we're supposed cap for illegals and stolen children? for a woman's right to choose
column2: equal pay and #metoo (which...nevermind) while not enough of them care about mass incarceration
column4: judicial reform or reparations. imagine if black men voted gop at 30%? imagine black women voting for alan keyes instead of michelle (if she were to run). we need to rethink our party affiliation and who our allies are cuz while the media and politics divide our community we are voting 90% the same
column5: we have lots of cash (1.3 trillion dollars)
column6: genius and talent. we have 3 continents of family with the wealthiest resources. long past time to unite. or

column1: 250197;instagram;2018-11-07 14:11:41;FALSE;"if life ran like fairy tales the person we fall for would not be the person who broke us. this is the real world
column4: we get hurt – over and over we stay

column6: abusive relationship for seven long years. plagued by the constant undeniable clamour that this isn’t how it’s meant to be. i watched my world become small
column7: as friends and family got taken out of the narrative. you would think bad relationships would be easy to leave but they can be the most difficult to walk away from.

column2: the more he saw the control he inflicted
column3: the greater his appetite for more. in a healthy relationship
column4: vulnerability is wonderful. it leads to increased intimacy and closer bonds. when a healthy person realises that he or she hurt you
column5: they feel remorse and they make amends. it’s safe to be honest.

column2: vulnerability is dangerous. abusive people feel a surge of power when they discover a weakness. they exploit it
column3: using it to gain more power. crying or complaining confirms that they’ve found the right spot.
but through habit. sometimes the bravest
column5: and most life-changing things lie not in what we do
column6: but in what we stop doing.

column1: then comes the next hurdle: living with your abusive past. finding yourself again and coming out the other end is a tough journey. i write this as fate has given me a chance to make a final stand against him. to stop him doing this to more women. i write this to you if your are or have been in a similar situation
column2: know that you are stronger then you think
column4: know that it does get better. i write this because i believe we should be open about our struggles about the things that break us and make us. our past does not determine our future. mental wounds heal if you allow it to happen. scars can become just a reminder of your struggles. they can show pain and suffering but more importantly
column5: they can show our will to survive.

column1: 250242;instagram;2018-11-07 11:07:10;FALSE;today i met a #kindred #spirit.  two actually.  one i’ve known for many years.  the second was a new acquaintance.  i felt her arrive before she walked into the cafe.  we greeted each other with a #kiss and a hug because it felt like the way kindred spirits should welcome each other.  we knew each other’s backstories which meant we could dispense with unnecessary chit chat.  it was refreshing.  at the end of our meeting she thanked me for ‘walking my talk’ and i thanked her for the same.  over the years i have been vocal about the need to rewrite and even reinvent our democracy in favour of a more #egalitarian #sustainable #society.  it has required considerable #commitment to that objective and actions that matched the words.  when we remain #true to our #values and follow our #conscience
column3: our actions bring benefits to many.  it hasn’t been easy but it is #rewarding for all the incredible people i’ve met along the way.  it feels like we are getting some #traction.  we are finding each other or should i say ‘divinely orchestrated’ from all over the world.  the job at hand is monumental.  dangerous even. yet it must be done and tonight as i reflect on this i feel wonderfully comforted by all the amazing people i know who are turning up and ‘walking their talk’. it takes a #community and we are ready! 💜 #rise #divinefeminine #metoo #timesup #sovereignty;;en;#kindred

column2: i went to university in london. i wanted to escape from my small life and go back to the city of my birth. i desperately wanted to be a london boy
column3: but quickly realised that it would never be my home. i was never going to fit in. all the attitude but none of the wisdom. lacking the understanding and lacking the accent. not accepted. not authentic. trying too hard to be a wide boy. another mask. another lie.

column1: once again all of my fears around my perceived inadequacies were alive within me. i had fled
column2: only for the fear and self-loathing i thought i’d escaped
column3: to track me down.  i clutched my masks tightly through that first term at university hoping that something or someone would come along and save me from myself.

everything changed. i found my place on the dancefloor. that small space became my promised land. my sanctuary. my hideaway. the most beautiful part of it was i could not dance wearing a mask; in those moments the mask melted away. i re-connected with my ten-year-old disco dancing self. that beautiful smiling happy boy who was yet to be beaten
column4: ashamed and angry."" excerpt from 'removing the masks' by spencer jacobs

column1: 250374;instagram;2018-11-07 10:09:08;FALSE;"unfortunately can't make this evening - other commitments but really honoured that my work has been popular that @bricklanegallery wanted to keep it longer.

here's the focus on this piece for me and there will be a more #astrological theme in future works. ""soulsearch - jupiter in scorpio"" ""the past few years co-creating my own life along with astrology and creativity i am expressing this journey through my work.
for 12 months jupiter the benefic guru an expansive energy in our inner and outer world has been transiting scorpio
column2: the zodiac sign that represents the deep unconscious
column7: taxes and inheritance... this work encourages us to not fear these areas but by exploration into the unconscious realms the healing process can begin.

column1: 250404;instagram;2018-11-07 08:52:46;FALSE;"⚡️new blog post⚡️which is a bit of a difficult one for me
column2: but it’s all about why i’m boycotting topshop and going #pinknotgreen. (link in bio - click on my profile pic to get to it!) the allegations against philip green have been difficult to watch unfold in the news and on social media
column3: and the fashion industry is going through its own #metoo movement with this story.

column1: as much as i love fashion and clothes (and as much as i love the satin skirt i bought there before this story came out)
column2: i can’t support a man who is such a prominent figure in his stores and the industry itself.

column1: it will be interesting to see how this story unfolds
column2: but in the meantime it just feels like the very least i could do.

column1: i would love to hear your thoughts on this - i’m definitely in the privileged position to be able to boycott a high street retailer
column2: but can completely understand those not in the same boat.
i’m definitely falling back in love with my blog again! i forget often how much i enjoy writing and don’t give myself enough time to get my thoughts out
column3: so it’s nice to get back into it! [📸: @ahphotographyinfo]";;en;#pinknotgreen.

column1: 250455;instagram;2018-11-07 08:08:20;FALSE;"reality check on divali & bandi shorr divas

bandi shorr in gurbani refers to guru sahib blessing you with liberation. this liberation has 2 ingredients your effort & the guru's grace. step forward & practice what guru jee teaches & embrace the grace.

divali on the majority is celebrated due to raam chandar defeating the demonic raavan & rescuing his kidnapped wife mata sita. the ramifications of this epic story are mostly lost on us today. #metoo has become a popular movement about speaking up about sexual abuse. today the same land that burns effigies of raavan & celebrates the return of mata sita has horrific rates of the most grotesque rapes & sexual abuse. isn't laxmi devi supposedly the form of all womanhood? mata sita was an avatar of laxmi. yet today the same womanhood that is revered in temples is raped on the streets of india. the effigies of rapists should be burnt but many roam free. nobody came to the rescue of these victims of rape - when will the proverbial raam chandar come to the rescue of these women?
the 6th guru of the sikhs was imprisoned in gwalior fort & successfully negotiated the release of 52 other kings who were falsely imprisoned. bandi shorr is the day this release was negotiated
column2: then after a long journey from gwalior to amritsar this freedom was celebrated on divali at amritsar.

column1: today the sikhs proclaim bhai jagtar singh hawara their jathedar/leader. yet we cannot even get him transferred to punjab let alone released. we cannot free ourselves of oppression let alone free others like guru sahib did.

today we gather at bargari seeking justice - peacefully protesting once again. protesting the continual desecration of sri guru granth sahib jee - which has become an unacceptable norm. singhs have given shaheedia. sri guru granth sahib jee keeps on giving shaheedi.

do what you can to tackle these evils. we need to grab the hem of the guru & he will become our bandi shorr in all that we face. for then the darkness of the moon less night (masiya) of divali will not effect us for then it will be lit up by the light of enlightenment & freedom. then we will have a happy divali or bandi shorr divas

column1: 250460;instagram;2018-10-26 06:55:46;FALSE;"more sneak peaks of our film program:
jules rosskam // 82 min // 2018 // english spoken language

paternal rites is a first-person essay film that examines the secret underbelly of a contemporary jewish american family as they grapple with the aftereffects of physical and sexual abuse on their present-day lives. it is also a groundbreaking film about the nature of trauma and memory itself: the ways in which trauma encrypts in uncanny ways; the function of speech and narrative in the process of decryption; and the role of film and filmmaking in the practice of healing. paternal rites draws inspiration from podcasts like this american life and radiolab and the long lineage of lgbt essay filmmakers in north america such as jenni olson
paternal rites ist ein essayfilm und handelt von der schattenseite einer zeitgenössischen jüdisch-amerikanischen familie

250509;instagram;2018-11-07 06:03:22;FALSE;"in 1807 new jersey became the last state to strip women of their right to vote.
over 41 years later the first women’s convention took place in 1848.
in 1866 susan b anthony and elizabeth cady stanton began the american equal rights association.
in 1872 susan b anthony was arrrested and fined for trying to vote.
in 1917 the national woman’s party picketed the white house and over 500 activists were arrested.  in 1920 after over 100 years of oppression
column2: the 15th amendment was passed and women were finally able to vote.
more than some of these women’s life times
column3: for the cry’s to be heard and the work to pay off. it took 72 years of women like elizabeth stanton
column5: and victoria woodhull (the first woman to run for presidency) having to face struggle
column6: adversity and seemed failures for change to happen. it took 72 years of women who were brave enough to stand against the grain and say ‘hey! thats not right’ before everyone was listening.

column1: when people ask why i’m a feminist it’s not because it’s cool
column2: or i like to be different
column3: it doesn’t mean i don’t want a man to hold the door for me
column4: and it’s certainly not because i hate all men... (all responses i’ve actually heard while wearing this shirt).

column1: i am a feminist because i’m willing to fight for equality
column2: and i’m willing to use my voice even when it’s unpopular. because not that long ago women actually had a lot less rights than men and if there wasn’t women who were brave enough to step into their voice
column3: and courageous enough to fight for change
column5: then it’s very possible i wouldn’t even have had a right to vote today. i’m not a feminist for myself
column6: i’m a feminist and i’m teaching my boys to be feminists for the future generations of women
column7: that they will have rights to their own choices for their bodies
column8: that they will not have to worry about gender pay gaps
column9: and that #metoo will only be something they have to read about in history books
column10: not something them and all their friends can relate so deeply too.

column1: it was since i first read 'why loiter?: women and risk on mumbai streets' by shilpa phadke
column2: i have been trying to capture the behavior pattern of women in public spaces in india. be it the metro cities or smaller towns
column3: it is usually seen problematic when a woman expresses the desire to have a chai at the local tapri/ tea-vendor or sing and walk freely on the streets. the idea of having gender inclusivity in our urban and rural spaces has a direct correlation with the woman's relationship with the city.

column1: these simple quotidian observations on a daily basis—particularly in public places like restaurants or marketplaces or malls or cinema-halls or parks or public squares (chowks)—make evident of their restricted body-languages and movement patterns. although they are manifested in multiple ways—like the manner of sitting
column2: having the gaze down while walking
column3: etc.—depending on the context and the level of acceptance in that space and place.

column1: voted like a mother today and i hope you did too. even if you’re not a mother. i hope you voted like a mother who’s six year old has to practice active shooter drills. vote like a mother who’s child is gay or transgender. vote like a mother who’s risking everything to try and make a better life for her child. vote like an immigrant mother who’s child was born on us soil and deserves an equal chance at the american dream. vote like a mother who’s black child wants to swim. or sell lemonade. or sleep in their dorm room. vote like a mother who wants a planet for future generations to live and love and grow on. you still have time. get out and vote! .
***oops forgot to add vote like a mother who believes her daughters sexual assault claims.**** .

column1: my mind tells me not to fall into the trap of your eyes
i’m in love with the idea of you
it says that i don’t really love you
i love the way i feel when i see you
the feeling of emptiness goes away
the feeling emptiness makes itself known
when i stare into your eyes
i drown into a sea of sadness
i try not to love you
i try to pull away from you
but the look on your eyes
just makes me fall harder than i did before
my mind says you don’t love me
my soul says to get out while i can but
i think i’m going to take the risk
i’m in love with the way you speak
i’m in love with your intelligence
how can i let go of you
how do i stop loving you?
this “lust” is taking up my energy
i have you in my arms
living in my own fantasy world
the feeling of lusting after you
the feeling of my heart being attached to you
not knowing how you feel about me is scary
i’ll l live in my world of delusion.

column4: while my mom is a u.s. citizen now
column6: she was an #undocumentedimmigrant decades ago. what many of you call “#illegal”. yes
column7: i was born to undocumented #immigrants. as you can guess
column8: i was the pathway to my parent’s green cards. eventually
column9: this allowed my mom to get her #american citizenship. i’m what many “red-blooded” americans call an #anchorbaby. but i’m an adult now

column3: the nra gave you an a rating! they loved you!
you said on twitter: “public officials should work for you
column4: not themselves”. — really?  so why 9 yrs ago when people asked you to change your stance for a more progressive one you didn’t? you wanted to win the upstate-ny conservative vote
column6: you did what you did for your own political gain! you worked for you!

column1: you’re good at that. so please don’t call what you do now an evolution
column2: it’s an insult to actual evolution. call it what it is
column3: political opportunism. today you’re all for undocumented immigrants & the #metoo movement… you even loudly remind us you’re lgbtq. you can pretend to be progressive
column4: but it doesn’t erase this: you do what you do
column5: not because you’ve genuinely evolved but
column6: because you’re an opportunist. you pretend to be “current” with the times
column7: to not lose your current seat. a flip-flopper for your own gain.

column1: 250710;instagram;2018-11-07 03:05:40;FALSE;"link in bio to the new blog. find out why you may find me crying on an airplane.

funny thing. last night i flew from toronto to nashville. the turbulence was almost unbearable as we headed into some serious storms bringing tornados below 🌪. i sat at the very back beside this really nice guy from canada 🇨🇦 who just happens to be a life coach. and one hell of a good one. he made me breathe through the turbulence
column2: listened to my fears and put me at ease to get through it. we had a good laugh when i told him my latest blog was entitled “i cry on planes”. thanks for calming my nerves keith. thanks to the pilot for getting us back on the ground safely and to my uber driver who braved the winds to drive me home. oh and a big thanks to me for not completely losing my sh$& in front of a bunch of strangers.

column1: i started @womenempowerx because i was a solo entrepreneur who felt extremely alone
column2: isolated and unsure of the next steps to take to turn my life around. ⠀

column1: i continued to wait for things to change until i realized nothing will change unless i do. ⠀
i needed not only the guidance but also the community. ⠀
wex was inspired by my own experiences of what i saw i needed as well as the hundreds of other women i began meeting through my speaking engagements. ⠀
the first year was incredible. the second year was transformational. the third year... will be life changing. ⠀⠀

column1: 250741;instagram;2018-11-07 02:29:04;FALSE;"i have my first therapy session this week.

i don't know when or how it got so bad. i think instead of dealing with all the pain.. i would push it deep down. bandage my wounds with alcohol. tell everyone i was fine. i'm strong. i don't need help. not me. ive been through hell. nothing can break me down.
well i hit that breaking point. i'm not okay. i feel utterly broken. and you know what!?! that's okay.
i've made the decision to embrace the pain and start working on myself and wading through all the shit i've buried deep down with the help of a trained professional.
it's okay to ask for help. mental health is just as important as physical health. and i'm excited to start this journey toward healing.

column1: 250761;instagram;2018-11-07 01:39:40;FALSE;when the australian google page has replaced its own name with a #govote heading for the american elections
column2: no one in the world can claim ignorance to the importance of this election!! you are not just voting for your country my american friends
column3: you are voting for all of ours too! we may not be eligible to vote in your election
column4: but the results are equally important and will affect us too! so do it for your fellow citizens of the world! in australia we have to vote
column5: we don’t get a choice. therefore i can’t say i’ve ever seen it as any great honour or privilege. however watching twitter and insta stories of people fighting to do it even when registered and fighting because their registration has mysteriously disappeared and performers of note manning phones on telethons and knocking on doors
column6: i realize it actually is. my say is handed to me and counted whether i appreciate it or not. although after witnessing this american election

column1: there’s a certain way you’re supposed to react to sexual assault. you’re supposed to feel a certain way. you’re supposed to report it. you’re supposed to go to your friends for support. you’re supposed to hate the person who did it to you.

column1: it felt like preaching to the choir.
i care less who you vote for
and more that you vote at all.
i won't judge you if you didn't
but i'll ask you to next time.
you don't have to be the most informed.
you don't have to make the perfect choice.
you just have to make a choice
all women and survivors (who we must believe)
my transgender sister (who will not be erased)
not just for all of the above.

column1: i grew up running around city hall visiting my grandfather at work. •

column2: i've gone with my parents to vote (which includes a lot of memories of my mother telling my father that he is not allowed to tell her how to vote
column3: nor is she required to tell him who she selected. this is also where i learned to plead the 5th). •

column1: i worked each election from the time i was 16 until i moved out of town. •
one of the biggest fights i ever had with my ex was when he refused to leave an event in time for us to go vote
when i moved to maine i got involved with our local political committee
column5: and i spend a lot of time calling

column1: i early voted because i wouldn't be in town for election day. •
i didn't work today because all of my babysitters were busy running the polling places. we still went to see judy harvey and the girls got to help out with making sure everything was in its place. •
my goal every day is to show my girls that their choices do make a difference. the choice can be whether to sit on the couch vs get up and move
column2: or whether to order pizza vs cook a healthy meal
column3: or be the swing vote that changes the world. the small choices they make add up to big changes in the long run. •

column2: domestic violence & sexual assault are so strong and courageous... even if it can feel like you are not. i had taken a break from instagram to deal with some issues surrounding my rape. recently
column3: and wonderful women inspired me to get back to posting. it’s crazy for me to believe that i educate
column4: help and inspire people. that people who i don’t know contact me with questions
column6: or seek advice. everyone who seeks any type assistance in any form after going through this type of ordeal is so strong and brave. when it happened to me i even was hesitant about seeking out people who might be able to help. while i still seek help at various times to deal with what happened to me
column7: i am so grateful and sometimes can’t even believe that at the same time
column8: i am also helping people. when i started my blog
column9: i told myself that i would be happy if i could just help one person. after two plus years
column10: it amazes me that i have exceeded my hopes to a vast degree. to all survivors...i stand with you! 💕

column1: 250833;instagram;2018-11-07 00:39:23;FALSE;"i find it extremely empowering and so important to exercise my right to vote. a right i do not take lightly. a right that so many before me have sacrificed so much so that i could be able to do this today.  not only that
column2: but i grew up in a communist country where voting was a big joke
column3: where everybody knew it was useless to go through the farce of voting because elections were rigged and dictatorship was alive and well for the foreseeable

column1: i myself have fought to gain the right to vote with the long and arduous process of becoming a us citizen almost two decades ago. my sense of civic duty has done a complete 180 since moving to the states and becoming a proud american citizen.  this amazing country of ours has taught me that my voice matters. that i matter!
i am so grateful to live in a society where my voice matters! i remind myself often that
column3: this is not the case in too many other parts of the world

column1: coincidentally (or perhaps not so much) i was listening to salma hayek’s recent interview on oprah’s super soul conversations podcast on my walk to the polls
column2: where she is discussing the #metoo and #timesup movement
column3: her views and her experiences in this context.  and it made me even more proud to be a woman. it made me feel even more empowered to use my voice to make a difference

column1: i will not let the disappointment from two years ago stop me from doing my part and from making a difference for the better
column2: as small as it may be. because every vote matters
column3: and every small action we take matters more than we sometimes believe it does. just like when i paint and i get frustrated many times at seemingly not improving my skills
column4: and yet looking back i can see the growth and progress i’ve made. i know that each time i pick up a brush and paint
column5: i am moving forward. i am manifesting change
column6: as imperceptible as it may seem to me!

column3: one small action at a time
column4: even if that change may be ever so subtle and slow. i know it all adds up to big changes over time. so #ivoted today to do my small part and to add my drop in the collective bucket. 💙

column1: nearly 4 months ago i received news that i never ever never even imagined could possibly be my truth.
for the last few months i have had to make a very intentional choice to continue to show up for my sobriety
column3: my children and the world every single day and sometimes moment by moment.•

column1: one thing that took a back seat
column2: even though still present was my consistent workouts and one thing that took a front seat was comfort food.

column1: let me be clear... i have zero regrets about this. because i also made some really intentional choices to pursue therapy
column2: loyal relationships with people i could trust to work through the unforeseen trauma
column3: and a very strong desire to continue to seek growth through love and forgiveness.•

column1: it hasn’t been easy and it’s certainly not over. but today i can finally say i absolutely see the light at the end of the tunnel. i have started to return to routines. i finally feel less anger and more calm.•
and so began today the return of the recorded workouts. i’m not aiming for size or weight this time
column2: i’m aiming for strength and sweat. and today i won those two things.💪🏼💦•

column1: thank you for my team of amazing humans who allow me to show up for them and have been here at the drop of a hat via text
column2: phone call or marco polo endlessly throughout all hours of the day.•

column1: 250865;instagram;2018-11-07 00:08:33;FALSE;"i read this morning on instagram that voting is a personal choice and that we shouldn’t “harass” others to vote if they don’t feel like it. so juvenile. i was saddened by the ignorance of this female “influencer”. 100 years ago women fought and sacrificed and protested in the women’s suffrage movement. it took women 80 years to win that 19th amendment to allow me the right to vote- just because i’m a woman. you simply cannot say #metoo and not vote.  imagine 80 years to get the right to say #metoo and vote. i stand today to be the example i was born to be. that my mother
column2: grandmother and great grandmother fought for me to be. whatever my ballot says
column5: and my duty. you may abstain as you have the right to also
column6: but when the time comes for you to complain about anything at all - remember you did not speak up when it was time. not voting truly is casting a vote.

column1: 250902;instagram;2018-11-06 23:47:08;FALSE;"“every election is determined by the people who show up.” did you show up today? #votethemout #voteforchange #voteordie •

welp...not this woman! 💁🏻‍♀️ i voted today and i’m proud because regardless of what happens

column3: people who don’t believe in my #metoo sisters when we say we’ve been raped
